SIMPLE: siege
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Siege
<hw>Siege</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sege</ets>,
OF. <ets>siege</ets>, F. <ets>si⟦egrave⟧ge</ets> a seat, a siege; cf.
It. <ets>seggia</ets>, <ets>seggio</ets>, <ets>zedio</ets>, a seat,
<ets>asseggio</ets>, <ets>assedio</ets>, a siege, F.
<ets>assi⟦eacute⟧ger</ets> to besiege, It. & LL. <ets>assediare</ets>,
L. <ets>obsidium</ets> a siege, besieging; all ultimately fr. L.
<ets>sedere</ets> to sit. See <er>Sit</er>, and cf. <er>See</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A seat; especially, a royal seat;
a throne.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Upon the very
<xex>siege</xex> of justice.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A stately <qex>siege</qex> of sovereign majesty,⟦br⟧
And thereon sat a woman gorgeous gay.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In our great hall there stood a vacant chair . . . ⟦br⟧
And Merlin called it ⟦ldquo⟧The <qex>siege</qex> perilous.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, place or situation; seat.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ah! traitorous eyes, come out of your shameless <qex>siege</qex>
forever.</q> <rj><qau>Painter (Palace of Pleasure).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Rank; grade; station; estimation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I fetch my life and being⟦br⟧
From men of royal <qex>siege</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Passage of excrements; stool; fecal matter.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>siege</qex> of this mooncalf.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The sitting of an army around or before a fortified
place for the purpose of compelling the garrison to surrender; the
surrounding or investing of a place by an army, and approaching it by
passages and advanced works, which cover the besiegers from the enemy's
fire. See the Note under <er>Blockade</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Hence, a continued attempt to gain
possession.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love stood the <qex>siege</qex>, and would not yield his
breast.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The floor of a glass-furnace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A workman's bench.</def>
<rj><au>Knught.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Siege gun</b></col>, <cd>a heavy gun for siege
operations.</cd> -- <col><b>Siege train</b></col>, <cd>artillery adapted
for attacking fortified places.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Siege</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Siege
<hw>Siege</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To besiege; to beset.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through all the dangers that can <qex>siege</qex>⟦br⟧
The life of man.</q> <rj><qau>Buron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Siegework</ent>⟦br⟧
